'''Paul S.C. Taçon''' (born 1958) is an anthropologist and archaeologist who has spent over thirty years conducting field work in destinations ranging from Australia, [[Botswana]], [[Cambodia]], Canada, China, India, [[Malaysia]], [[Myanmar]], [[Thailand]], [[South Africa]] and the United States. In 2011, he was appointed the first Chair in [[Rock Art]] research<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.griffith.edu.au/humanities-languages/school-humanities/research/protect-australias-spirit |title=Protect Australia’s Spirit - Griffith University |publisher=Griffith.edu.au |date=May 31, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117223527/http://www.griffith.edu.au/humanities-languages/school-humanities/research/protect-australias-spirit |archivedate=January 17, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> at [[Griffith University]] on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], Australia. Paul S.C. Taçon has made several key archaeological discoveries in Australia, most notably in western [[Arnhem Land]] (NT) and [[Wollemi National Park]] (NSW). These include the earliest rock art evidence of warfare in the world,<ref>{{cite web|author=Paul Taçona1 and Christopher Chippindalea2 |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayFulltext?type=1&fid=2822380&jid=CAJ&volumeId=4&issueId=02&aid=2822372 |title=Cambridge Journals Online - Abstract |doi=10.1017/S0959774300001086 |publisher=Journals.cambridge.org |date=December 22, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref> the origins of the [[Rainbow Serpent]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cFQSNAAACAAJ&redir_esc=y |title=Birth of the Rainbow Serpent in ... - Paul Stephen Charles Tacon, Christopher Chippindale, Meredith Wilson - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com.au |date=September 12, 2000 |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboriginalartonline.com/culture/rainbow.php |title=Rainbow Serpent and the Dreamtime |publisher=Aboriginal Art Online |date= |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref> significant new Arnhem Land rock art sites,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/rocks-of-ages-millenniums-in-pictures/2008/09/19/1221331207186.html |title=Rocks of ages: millenniums in pictures - World |publisher=smh.com.au |date= September 20, 2008|accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=May |first=Sally |url=https://anu.academia.edu/SallyMay/Papers/796886/Ancient_bird_stencils_discovered_in_Arnhem_Land_Northern_Territory_Australia |title=Ancient bird stencils discovered in Arnhem Land, Northern Territory, Australia (Sally May) - Academia.edu |publisher=Anu.academia.edu |date= |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Traci Watson Contributor |url=http://www.aolnews.com/2010/05/29/louvre-on-the-rocks-cache-of-aborignal-art-revealed/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120720160633/http://www.aolnews.com/2010/05/29/louvre-on-the-rocks-cache-of-aborignal-art-revealed/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=July 20, 2012 |title=Cache of Aboriginal Art Revealed in Djulirri Rock Shelter in Australia |publisher=Aolnews.com |date=May 29, 2010 |accessdate=December 16, 2011 }}</ref> rock art discoveries in Wollemi National Park <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/wollemi-find-an-aboriginal-seat-of-the-gods/2007/04/20/1176697093038.html |title=Wollemi find an Aboriginal seat of the gods - National |publisher=smh.com.au |date=April 20, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/09/26/1064083186183.html |title=Songlines across the Wollemi |publisher=www.smh.com.au |date= September 27, 2003|accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/catalyst/stories/s968475.htm |title=Catalyst: Wollemi Rock Art - ABC TV Science |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=October 16, 2003 |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diamondspirit.net/adunk/WollemiRockArtTimeline.html |title=Timeline of recent rock art discoveries in Wollemi |publisher=Diamondspirit.net |date= |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref> and the oldest rock paintings of Southeast Asian watercraft in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-07-17/australias-oldest-painting-prompts-history-rethink/908036?section=justin |title=Australia's oldest painting prompts history rethink - Just In (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=July 17, 2010 |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=&nbsp; |url=http://www.australianews.com.au/story?cityid=d1de82e1-fce9-4f45-9541-79d83e888155&storyid=332f830c-893d-4fa1-a29d-46dd9ce663f8 |title=Australia's oldest painting prompts history rethink |publisher=AustraliaNews.com.au |date=July 17, 2010 |accessdate=December 16, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606070334/http://www.australianews.com.au/story?cityid=d1de82e1-fce9-4f45-9541-79d83e888155&storyid=332f830c-893d-4fa1-a29d-46dd9ce663f8 |archivedate=June 6, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>
==Career== Paul S.C. Taçon received his MA in [[Anthropology]] from [[Trent University]] in 1984 and his PhD from the [[Australian National University]] in 1990. He was based at the [[Australian Museum]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Australia |url=http://www.australianmuseum.net.au/ |title=nature, culture, discover |publisher=Australian Museum |date= |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref> in Sydney from 1991 to 2005, acting as a principal research scientist in anthropology from 1998 to 2005 and Head of the Museum's People and Place Research Centre from 1995 to 2003. In 2005, Paul S.C. Taçon joined [[Griffith University]] and has since led two ongoing research programs, "Picturing Change" and "Late Pleistocene Peopling of East Asia".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.griffith.edu.au/humanities-languages/school-humanities/staff/professor-paul-tacon |title=Professor Paul Taçon - Griffith University |publisher=Griffith.edu.au |date= |accessdate=December 16, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328100713/http://www.griffith.edu.au/humanities-languages/school-humanities/staff/professor-paul-tacon |archivedate=March 28, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He has pioneered the use of [[radiocarbon dating]] of [[beeswax]] rock art,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mc2.vicnet.net.au/home/date/web/tuniz.html |title=Dating Australian Rock-Markings: An Interdisciplinary Challenge |publisher=Mc2.vicnet.net.au |date= |accessdate=December 16, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407025215/http://mc2.vicnet.net.au/home/date/web/tuniz.html |archivedate=April 7, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and his research team was the first to use [[uranium]]-series direct dates for rock art in China.<ref>{{cite web|last=Aubert |first=Maxime |url=https://uow.academia.edu/MaximeAubert/Papers/1177530/Uranium-series_age_estimates_for_rock_art_in_southwest_China |title=Uranium-series age estimates for rock art in southwest China (Maxime Aubert) - Academia.edu |publisher=Uow.academia.edu |date= |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref> Currently, he is leading the use of innovative three-dimensional laser scanners to conserve vulnerable rock art sites.
==Place, Evolution and Rock Art Heritage Unit== Paul S.C. Taçon recently established the Place, Evolution and Rock Art Heritage Unit (PERAHU) at Griffith University. This research unit is located within the [https://web.archive.org/web/20120104214934/http://www.griffith.edu.au/humanities-languages/school-humanities School of Humanities] and advocates multidisciplinary, multicultural and scientific approaches to rock art and cultural evolution research. He has close collaborations with the [http://rsh.anu.edu.au/rockart/ Rock Art Research Centre] at the [[Australian National University]] and the [http://www.uwa.edu.au/rock-art/research Centre for Rock-Art Studies] at the [[University of Western Australia]]. Together, these three research groups are the foremost authority on rock art research in Australia.
=="Protect Australia’s Spirit” campaign== He recently launched the “[https://web.archive.org/web/20110803215633/http://www.protectaustraliasspirit.com.au/viewPage/index.cfm?pageId=1 Protect Australia’s Spirit]” campaign <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.griffith.edu.au/humanities-languages/school-humanities/research/protect-australias-spirit |title=Protect Australia’s Spirit - Griffith University |publisher=Griffith.edu.au |date=May 31, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117223527/http://www.griffith.edu.au/humanities-languages/school-humanities/research/protect-australias-spirit |archivedate=January 17, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> in May 2011 with actor [[Jack Thompson (actor)|Jack Thompson]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/jack-thompson-acts-to-preserve-rock-art/story-e6frg6nf-1226066014500 | first=Leigh | last=Dayton | title=Jack Thompson acts to preserve rock art | date=May 31, 2011 | work=The Australian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Foster |first=Margot |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rural/telegraph/content/2011/s3231725.htm |title=Protect Australia's Spirit - a campaign to save our rock art - 31/05/2011 |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=May 31, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref> This campaign aims to create a fully resourced national archive to bring together information about rock art sites, as well as planning for future rock art management and conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2011/s3231743.htm |title=The World Today - Campaign for Aboriginal rock art database 31/05/2011 |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=October 2, 1980 |accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref>
